track_notes:
Hiked in 2022 October. To save a good amount of ascent and over a mile distance round trip, you can do cross-country approach from Windy Ridge TH 985. There were an old trail here. Recent forest fire made ground soft, but still good progress can be made. Recommend to stay on ridge line for easier travel. Climb the most northern peak of Buffalo N-S ridge to avoid steep talus and ravine below this corner peak. Move S on the ridge. Circumnavigate the 2nd peak from East. Very good flat ground for camping after this peak and before Buffalo.
Go around Buffalo on the West side. This is steep and a bit dense, but short. Summit base is not in AZ! I measured that the first balcony is in AZ by 2-3 feet. You may do your own measurement. There were 2 registers on the summit. Climb is Class 3. Some exposed move required. Rotten rock. Rappel point mid-way at an old tree.

Hiked in 2022 August. Recent forest fire burned down most of the lower east side of the creek. There are many trees across the trail. You may lose the trail as well. Once you cross the creek the 2nd time the trail can be a bit overgrown before the talus field. Upper section was not affected by the fires. Once reached the saddle turn east and up towards Buffalo. Approach is easy, circumnavigate first large peak and you will be at summit base. Summit base is not in activation zone. There is a balcony as you walk north next to summit base and you will be blocked by it. If you climb this outcrop you find yourself on the first balcony. According to my measurement this balcony was just in the AZ by 2-3 feet in 2022. To climb the summit you can start from summit base or this balcony. The balcony is the base of a chimney, and a small narrow ledge. Easiest route is the ledge, but even this requires some exposed moves. There was a rappel rope attached to a dead tree half way up.
